# Stack

Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS. Tailwind chosen for speed — no separate CSS files, no styled-components, no extra build config.

Setup:
```
npx create-next-app@latest frontend --typescript --tailwind --app --eslint
cd frontend
npm run dev
```

# Project structure

```
frontend/
  app/
    layout.tsx
    page.tsx
    items/
      page.tsx              # one folder per route
  components/                  # reusable UI, PascalCase filenames
    ItemCard.tsx
  lib/
    api.ts                       # fetch wrapper for backend calls
    types.ts                      # shared TS types matching backend schemas
  .env.local
  .env.example
```

# lib/api.ts pattern

```ts
const API_URL = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL ?? "http://localhost:8000";

export async function apiFetch<T>(path: string, options?: RequestInit): Promise<T> {
  const res = await fetch(`${API_URL}${path}`, {
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    ...options,
  });

  if (!res.ok) {
    const body = await res.json().catch(() => null);
    throw new Error(body?.detail ?? `Request failed: ${res.status}`);
  }

  return res.json();
}
```

All backend calls go through this — no `fetch()` scattered directly inside components. One place to change if the error shape or base URL changes.

# lib/types.ts pattern

```ts
export type Item = {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  price: number;
};

export type ItemCreate = {
  name: string;
  price: number;
};
```

Keep this in sync with the backend's `schemas/` — a schema change on the backend means updating this file in the same task.

# Server vs Client components

- Server Components by default (no `"use client"`). Fetch data directly in the component with `await apiFetch(...)`.
- Add `"use client"` only when the component needs `useState`, `useEffect`, event handlers, or browser-only APIs — typically forms and interactive widgets, not data-display components.
- Don't mark a whole page `"use client"` just because one small part of it needs interactivity — pull that part into its own small client component instead.

Example server component fetching data:
```tsx
// app/items/page.tsx
import { apiFetch } from "@/lib/api";
import { Item } from "@/lib/types";

export default async function ItemsPage() {
  const items = await apiFetch<Item[]>("/items");
  return (
    <ul className="space-y-2">
      {items.map((item) => (
        <li key={item.id} className="rounded border p-3">{item.name} — ${item.price}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

Example client component for a form:
```tsx
"use client";
import { useState } from "react";
import { apiFetch } from "@/lib/api";
import { ItemCreate } from "@/lib/types";

export default function NewItemForm() {
  const [name, setName] = useState("");
  const [price, setPrice] = useState(0);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  async function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent) {
    e.preventDefault();
    setLoading(true);
    setError(null);
    try {
      await apiFetch<Item>("/items", {
        method: "POST",
        body: JSON.stringify({ name, price } satisfies ItemCreate),
      });
    } catch (err) {
      setError(err instanceof Error ? err.message : "Something went wrong");
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit} className="space-y-2">
      <input value={name} onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)} className="border p-2 rounded w-full" placeholder="Name" />
      <input type="number" value={price} onChange={(e) => setPrice(Number(e.target.value))} className="border p-2 rounded w-full" placeholder="Price" />
      {error && <p className="text-red-600 text-sm">{error}</p>}
      <button disabled={loading} className="rounded bg-black text-white px-4 py-2">
        {loading ? "Saving..." : "Add item"}
      </button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

# Conventions

- TypeScript everywhere, no `.js`/`.jsx` files. No `any` unless there's genuinely no time to type it — leave `// TODO: type this`.
- Every data-fetching component handles loading and error state — even a bare `if (error) return <p>...</p>` is enough, don't skip it.
- Styling: Tailwind utility classes directly in JSX. Extract to a `components/` file once a pattern repeats 3+ times, not before.
- Keep components small and route-scoped. Don't build a generic design system mid-hackathon.
- Forms: plain controlled inputs + `useState` (as above) unless the form is genuinely complex — don't reach for `react-hook-form` or `zod` just for a 2-field form, it's setup time you don't need.
- Don't add a state-management library (Redux, Zustand, etc.). `useState` + passing props, or React Context for something truly global (e.g. current user), is enough at hackathon scale.

# Security basics

- Only expose values through `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` that are genuinely safe for the browser — never put backend secrets/API keys behind that prefix.
- Never render untrusted HTML with `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`; let React escape values by default.
- Treat data from the API as untrusted for display — the backend validates, but don't build URLs or eval anything from user/API input.
- Keep secret-dependent calls (private API keys, server-only tokens) in Server Components / route handlers, not client components.

# Common gotchas

- Hydration mismatch errors usually mean something (like `Date.now()` or `Math.random()`) is rendered differently on server vs client — compute it in a `useEffect` on the client instead if it must be dynamic.
- App Router `fetch()` caches by default. If data looks stale during a demo, add `{ cache: "no-store" }` to the fetch options for that call.
- CORS errors in the browser console mean the backend's `cors_origins` doesn't include `http://localhost:3000` — fix it on the backend, not by adding headers on the frontend.
- Forgetting `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix means an env var is silently `undefined` in the browser — server-only vars don't need the prefix, client-used vars must have it.

# Deployment (if needed for the demo)

Vercel is the fastest path for a Next.js app — connect the repo, set `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` to wherever the backend ends up, done. Don't spend hackathon time on a custom deployment pipeline.
